body.body:
gdb version sha:e86ca25fd6cc06488c9dda936cf83f0fcdf6b58b (17-Apr-2018)
removed TYPE_TAG_NAME in favour of TYPE_NAME to 'simplify' usage. the
fallout due to the new implementation in 'gdb/python/py-type.c'
resulting in premature removal of the 'struct' identifier that the go
'SliceTypePrinter' was using to match on

fix adds a trivial 'TypePrinter' base class to allow for a specialised
'match()' in the 'SliceTypePrinter' class which considers the type's
structure in addition to its (now simplified) type name

-----

Bisecting gdb resulted in this being the pivot:
```
commit e86ca25fd6cc06488c9dda936cf83f0fcdf6b58b (refs/bisect/bad)
Author: Tom Tromey <tom@tromey.com>
Date:   Tue Apr 17 13:51:24 2018 -0600

    Remove TYPE_TAG_NAME
```
I believe the relevant part is as follows:
```diff
iff --git a/gdb/python/py-type.c b/gdb/python/py-type.c
index 80055b05e0..dd8c0aa9dc 100644
--- a/gdb/python/py-type.c
+++ b/gdb/python/py-type.c
@@ -416,10 +416,16 @@ static PyObject *
 typy_get_tag (PyObject *self, void *closure)
 {
   struct type *type = ((type_object *) self)->type;
+  const char *tagname = nullptr;
 
-  if (!TYPE_TAG_NAME (type))
+  if (TYPE_CODE (type) == TYPE_CODE_STRUCT
+      || TYPE_CODE (type) == TYPE_CODE_UNION
+      || TYPE_CODE (type) == TYPE_CODE_ENUM)
+    tagname = TYPE_NAME (type);
+
+  if (tagname == nullptr)
     Py_RETURN_NONE;
-  return PyString_FromString (TYPE_TAG_NAME (type));
+  return PyString_FromString (tagname);
 }
 /* Return the type, stripped of typedefs. */
```
## gdb debug sessions
### good (pre-breaking change)
```
(gdb) ptype
type = struct []int32 {
    int32 *array;
    int len;
    int cap;
}
(gdb) p arr
$3 = []int32 = {1, 2, 4, 5, 7, 8, 10}

(gdb) python import pdb
(gdb) python pdb.run('gdb.execute("print arr")')
> <string>(1)<module>()
..
(Pdb) n
> /usr/lib/go/src/runtime/runtime-gdb.py(225)matcher()
-> if klass.pattern.match(str(val.type)):
(Pdb) p str(val.type)
'struct []int32'
(Pdb)
```
### bad (e86ca25fd6cc06488c9dda936cf83f0fcdf6b58b)
```
(gdb) ptype arr
type = struct []int32 {
    int32 *array;
    int len;
    int cap;
}
(gdb) p arr
$1 = {array = 0xc0000142a0, len = 7, cap = 8}

(gdb) python import pdb
(gdb) python pdb.run('gdb.execute("print arr")')
...
(Pdb) n
-> def matcher(val):
(Pdb) p val
<gdb.Value object at 0x7f7e8b9ba070>
(Pdb) print(val)
{array = 0xc00001a2a0, len = 7, cap = 8}
...
(Pdb) n
> /usr/lib/go/src/runtime/runtime-gdb.py(225)matcher()
-> if klass.pattern.match(str(val.type)):
(Pdb) p klass
<class '__main__.SliceTypePrinter'>
(Pdb) p klass.pattern
re.compile('^struct \\[\\]')
(Pdb) p str(val.type)
'[]int32'
(Pdb) gdb.execute('ptype arr')
type = struct []int32 {
    int32 *array;
    int len;
    int cap;
}
```
The difference is in the `p str(val.type)` result, the `"struct "` prefix has gone. Following this patch the original behaviour is restored.

Testing environment used go v1.12.6, and dozens of gdb versions up to HEAD.
body.title: runtime: fix gdb pretty print for slices

This CL fixes this behavior adding an error check on close functions, and returning an error in case the pipe read/write is already closed and keeping the first error still available.

`atomicError` has been removed and changed for a mutex because the check needs.

Fixes #24283

body.body:
GO uses AddVectoredExceptionHandler/AddVectoredContinueHandler on
Windows to setup its handling of exceptions on Windows (for recovering
from some kind of exceptions like divide by zero and various overflows
situations that can be handled nicely in Go). In the context of CGO, the
registered exception/continue handlers use isgoexception() to determine
if they should handle the exception, or let whatever other handler has
been registered do its work (typical exemple, is when calling C/C++ code
with CGO, and having a C debugger introducing a breakpoint in non-go
code).

The last handler in the chain misses this check. This is usually ok, but
in some cases, when a user attaches a non-go debugger to a CGO enabled
process, non-go breakpoints can actually be catched by this handler which
panics and stop the execution.

The problem was discovered by building a go package in c-shared mode,
and using it from a C# application. Whenever a go routine callbacks a
a function defined in C#, it panics if the .Net debugger is attached
(and runs fine otherwise).

This commit fixes this behavior by ignoring exceptions originating from
non-go code in the last continue handler.
body.title: runtime: ignore exceptions from non-go code in lastcontinuehandler on Windows

body.body:
With this patch, many projects using vendor.conf format should be able
to transition to go mod.

Example of a problematic line in cmd/go/internal/modconv/testdata/moby.out:

  github.com/go-check/check 4ed411733c5785b40214c70bce814c3a3a689609 https://github.com/cpuguy83/check.git

In vendor.conf format, the third column represents the URL of a fork
repository which was being ignored before this patch.

Because of this, go mod was incorrectly assuming the revision (4ed...609)
exists in the upstream github.com/go-check/check when in fact it only does
in the github.com/cpuguy83/check fork.

One cannot simply expect a user to change github.com/go-check/check to
github.com/cpuguy83/check because the import path in both cases is
github.com/go-check/check.

For that example, this patch would do the equivalent of:
  go mod edit -require=github.com/go-check/check@latest
              -replace=github.com/go-check/check=github.com/cpuguy83/check@4ed411733c5785b40214c70bce814c3a3a689609
body.title: cmd/go: honor vendor.conf fork repositories in modconv

body.body:
to avoid two bugs mentioned in https://github.com/golang/go/issues/29469.

Go specification says: A value x is assignable to a variable of type T if x
is a bidirectional channel value, T is a channel type, x's type V and T have 
identical element types, and at least one of V or T is not a defined type. 
However, the current reflection implementation is incorrect which makes
"x is assignable to T" even if type V and T are both defined type.

The current reflection implementation also mistakes the base types of two
non-defined pointer types share the same underlying type when the two
base types satisfy the above mentioned special channel assignability rule.

Fixes https://github.com/golang/go/issues/29469
body.title: reflect: seperate the special channel assignability rule from haveIdenticalUnderlyingType

As https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2616#page-117 says: 

HTTP/1.1 defines the "close" connection option for the sender to signal that the connection will be closed after completion of the response.

But it does not specify the connection should be closed by client or server, for safety, if `Connection: close`
is set in response header, server should close the connection after write data. Recently we have been
affect by this issue: we write a lots of data to client, but the client does not close the connection(
keep-alive is set by default in HTTP/1.1), so memory is still hold by `response`, and memory is used up.
body.title: net/http: close connection if `Connection: close` is set

A fix that will allow for annotating cdata and chardata with
names and nested elements. e.g. `a-name,cdata` or `a>b>c,cdata`.
A typical usecase might be marshling to json and xml is requierd
and reducing the need for mapping the sturct to others.

Fixes #16198

Some reflection.
I'm not familiar with this code base and there might be some more
corner case that i'm missing in the addition to the tests i've added.

There is also a risk that the way of annotating might end up some
what confusing which might be worth considering. eg. 
`Name string`, turns into `<struct><Name>..</Name></struct>`
`Name string 'xml:"name"'`, turns into `<struct><name>..</name></struct>`
`Name string 'xml:",cdata"'` turns into `<struct><![CDATA[...]]></struct>`
`Name string 'xml:"name,cdata"'` turns into `<struct><name><![CDATA[...]]></name></struct>`

I would however argue that is still provides a needed feature 

There is also a case to be made that the same principle should apply
of annotation with innerxml as for cdata and chardata.

body.body:
The current glob pattern implementation in `match.go` does not provide any way to learn if pattern is valid.

It does not help to call `Match(pattern, s)` to test if you get an error, because depending on `s` this might not return an error even though the pattern is invalid (like `Match("a[", "a")`).

As patterns are often provided by the user, it would be great to have a way to validate the pattern when reading the user input.

This PR implements `IsPatternValid(pattern)` to validate glob patterns. If `IsPatternValid(pattern)` returns `true`, you can be sure that `Match(pattern, s)` will never return an error.
body.title: path/filepath: implement IsPatternValid(pattern)

This change modifies Go to encode null slices and maps as [] and {} respectively.

Below is From https://github.com/golang/go/issues/27589:
==========
There have been many reports about encoding a nil slice or map as [ ] or { } respectively.

See: #2278

Currently it is encoded as null. This is a source of bugs in many non-theoretical cases (eg consumers of JSON APIs). There are many issues on Google about others falling into this pitfall so it is at least not uncommon.

It would be nice if a struct tag can be used to signify that we intend the nil slice or map to be treated as an empty slice or map respectively for the purposes of marshalling.

Current solutions include: https://github.com/helloeave/json. This is not a nice solution because it requires the assistance of a third-party package.

This is how it's implemented in third party lib: helloeave/json@7b6e442

Share a slice backing between the host address, network ip and mask. Add tests to verify that each slice header has len==cap to prevent introducing new behavior into Go programs. This has a small tradeoff of allocating a larger slice backing when the address is invalid. Earlier error detection of invalid prefix length helps balance this cost and a new benchmark for ParseCIDR helps measure it.

This yields a 22%~ speedup for all nil err cidr tests:
```
  name               old time/op    new time/op    delta
  ParseCIDR/IPv4-24    9.17µs ± 6%    7.20µs ± 7%  -21.47%  (p=0.000 n=20+20)
  ParseCIDR/IPv6-24    9.02µs ± 6%    6.95µs ± 9%  -23.02%  (p=0.000 n=20+20)
  ParseCIDR/IPv4-24    1.51kB ± 0%    1.55kB ± 0%   +2.65%  (p=0.000 n=20+20)
  ParseCIDR/IPv6-24    1.51kB ± 0%    1.55kB ± 0%   +2.65%  (p=0.000 n=20+20)
  ParseCIDR/IPv4-24      68.0 ± 0%      34.0 ± 0%  -50.00%  (p=0.000 n=20+20)
  ParseCIDR/IPv6-24      68.0 ± 0%      34.0 ± 0%  -50.00%  (p=0.000 n=20+20)
```

Including non-nil err cidr tests gains around 25%~:
```
  name               old time/op    new time/op    delta
  ParseCIDR/IPv4-24    11.8µs ±11%     8.9µs ± 8%  -24.88%  (p=0.000 n=20+20)
  ParseCIDR/IPv6-24    11.7µs ± 7%     8.7µs ± 5%  -25.93%  (p=0.000 n=20+20)
  ParseCIDR/IPv4-24    1.98kB ± 0%    2.00kB ± 0%   +1.21%  (p=0.000 n=20+20)
  ParseCIDR/IPv6-24    1.98kB ± 0%    2.00kB ± 0%   +1.21%  (p=0.000 n=20+20)
  ParseCIDR/IPv4-24      87.0 ± 0%      48.0 ± 0%  -44.83%  (p=0.000 n=20+20)
  ParseCIDR/IPv6-24      87.0 ± 0%      48.0 ± 0%  -44.83%  (p=0.000 n=20+20)
```

If GOHOSTOS == GOOS || GOHOSTARCH == GOARCH the go build system assume
it's not cross compiling and uses the same compiler for both
CC_FOR_TARGET and CC even if they are declared different. During go
compilation, this produces the error:

fork/exec
/accts/mlweber1/rclinux/rc-buildroot-test/scripts/instance-2/output/build/host-go-1.10/bin/go:
no such file or directory

cause the go binary produced is linked against a different libc and
cannot be run on the host machine.

This is a problem in case the cross compilation mandates a different
toolchain for host and target like happens in cross compilation
environments like buildroot. This patch adds GO_ASSUME_CROSSCOMPILING
varible to assure that in case of cross compilation CC_FOR_TARGET can be
different from CC.

Fixes #25177

go/build.Import failed to assign values .ImportPath and .Root if a package is a local import and is a sub package of testdata. Then in cmd/go/internal/load.VendoredImportPath, the vendored import path is not expanded if the parent.Root is empty. Without the "vendor" part in the parent package, the check `filepath.Join(root, parent.ImportPath) != dir` in cmd/go/internal/load.VendoredImportPath succeeds in child imports, leading to #24854.

This PR makes go/build assign .ImportPath and .Root for a testdata package in GOPATH properly, and fixes #24854.
